'''Frank Pommersheim''' is an American professor, author, and poet specializing in the field of [[Native Americans in the United States|American Indian law]]. Pommersheim is serving on several tribal appellate courts and serves as the [[Chief Justice]] for the [[Cheyenne River Indian Reservation|Cheyenne River Sioux Tribal Court of Appeals]] and the Rosebud Sioux Supreme Court<ref name="Arguing with Tradition Book">{{cite book|last1=Richland|first1=Justin B.|title=Arguing with Tradition: The Language of Law in Hopi Tribal Court|date=Sep 15, 2008|publisher=University of Chicago Press|page=13}}</ref> and is also notable for his involvement in [[The Camden 28]].<ref name="Camden POV Doc">{{cite web|last1=Giacchino|first1=Anthony|title="The Camden 28". POV Documentaries with a Point of View|url=https://www.pbs.org/pov/camden28/|publisher=Public Broadcasting Corporation|accessdate=2013}}</ref><ref name="Peace Warriors Book Camden">{{cite book|last1=McGowan|first1=Edward|title=Peace warriors : the story of the Camden 28|date=2001|publisher=Circumstantial Productions Pub.|location=Nyack, N.Y.|isbn=1891592130}}</ref>

==Early life and education==
Frank Pommersheim was born in New York City but moved to the [[Rosebud Indian Reservation|Rosebud Sioux Reservation]] in 1974 where he worked for 10 years before joining the [[University of South Dakota]] faculty in 1984.<ref name="USD Bio" /> Pommersheim graduated in 1965 with a Bachelor of Arts from [[Colgate University]]. He earned a [[Juris Doctor|J.D.]] from [[Columbia Law School]] in 1968 and a [[Master of Public Administration|MPA]] from [[Harvard University]].

Pommersheim was employed as the Director of Dakota Plains Legal Service from 1980-1983. As a Senior Consumer Law Specialist for the New York City Department of  Consumer Affairs from 1971-1973 and as an Attorney and Volunteer Leader for the VISTA program in Alaska from 1968-1970.<ref name="USD Bio" />

==Career==
Frank Pommersheim began teaching at the [[University of South Dakota School of Law]] in 1984 where he is currently a professor specializing in [[Native Americans in the United States|American Indian law]].<ref name="Dartmouth Newspaper">{{cite web|last1=Aylward|first1=Casey|title=Talk focuses on Indian relations|url=http://thedartmouth.com/2010/04/21/news/talk-focuses-on-indian-relations|website=http://thedartmouth.com/|publisher=The Dartmouth (Newspaper)|accessdate=27 June 2014}}</ref> Pommersheim has also taught at the [[Lewis & Clark Law School]], [[University of Tulsa College of Law]], College of Law in Dublin, Ireland, Sinte Gleska University, and the [[University of New Mexico]].

Pommersheim serves on tribal [[appellate court]]s and is currently the Chief Justice for the Cheyenne River Sioux Tribal Court of Appeals as well as Associate Justice for the Rosebud Sioux Supreme Court.<ref name="USD Bio">{{cite web|title=Frank Pommersheim Bio|url=https://www.usd.edu/law/frankpommersheim.cfm|publisher=University of South Dakota School of Law|accessdate=2013}}</ref>

