==Involvement  in the Camden 28==
[[Image:Camden 28 FBI surveillance.jpg|right|thumb|FBI surveillance photo of three of the [[Camden 28]] lurking outside the draft board offices in the morning hours of August 22, 1971.]]
'''The Camden 28''' were an eclectic group of  anti-[[Vietnam War]] activists. The group included young students, blue-collar workers, four Catholic priests and a Protestant minister. In 1971 they planned and executed a The Camden 28 raided a Camden, New Jersey draft board and destroyed records containing [[Selective Service System|Class 1-A status]] draft registrants.<ref name=Camden.org>{{cite web|title=The Camden 28|url=http://www.camden28.org/master.html?http://www.camden28.org/camden28.htm|website=TheCamden28.org|accessdate=27 June 2014}}</ref> Pommersheim, who was appropriately 28 at the time, was a member of this group's anti-Vietnam War activists. The group faced felony charges for their actions, but subsequently were acquitted by a jury in 1973. The high-profile trial against the activists that was seen by many as a referendum on the Vietnam War and as an example of successful use of [[jury nullification]].<ref>{{citation|title=Jury nullification: The contours of a controversy|author=A Scheflin, J Van Dyke|publisher=Law & Contemp. Probs.|year=1979|url=http://heinonlinebackup.com/hol-cgi-bin/get_pdf.cgi?handle=hein.journals/lcp43&section=49}}</ref> In 2007, [[PBS]] produced [[The Camden 28 (film)]] a documentary on the event and the events surrounding it. [[Howard Zinn]] testified at the trial and [[Supreme Court Justice]] [[William J. Brennan Jr.|William Brennan]] called the trial, "one of the great trials of the 20th century".<ref>{{cite news |first=Matt Zoller |last=Seitz |title=A Draft-Board Break-In That Put Activism on Trial |date=July 27, 2007 |accessdate=May 1, 2016 |website=The New York Times |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2007/07/27/movies/27camd.html}}</ref>

== Personal life ==
Frank married a fellow member of the [[The Camden 28|Camden 28]], Anne Dunham.  The couple left the East coast and lived and worked on the [[Rosebud Indian Reservation]] in South Dakota for 10 years. Anne and Frank later moved to Vermillion, South Dakota. They have three children.<ref name="Television Interview">{{cite news|title=Conversations with Frank Pommersheim|url=http://www.sdpb.org/home/|accessdate=2013|newspaper=South Dakota Public Television|date=1990}}</ref> Pommersheim is personal friends with [[Bob Dylan]] and a passionate fan of folk music.

== Books ==
* Broken Landscape: Indians, Indian Tribes and the Constitution (Oxford University Press, 2009)
*Felix Cohen's Handbook of Federal Indian Law (contributor) (2005 Ed.)
* Braid of Feathers: American Indian Law and Contemporary Tribal Life (University of California Press 1995; paperback ed. 1997)
* Reservation Street Law (with Anita Remerowski) (Sinte Gleska College Press 1979)
* Broken Ground and Flowing Waters: An Introductory Text on Rosebud Sioux Tribal Government (Sinte Gleska College Press 1977)

== Poetry ==
* Small is Beautiful:  The Buddha Correspondence (Chapbook, Rose Hill Books, 2011)
* East of the River:  Poems Both Ancient and New (Rose Hills Books, 2008)
* Haiku for the Birds (Rose Hill Books, 2002)
* Mindfulness and Home: Poetry and Prose from a Prairie Landscape (Rose Hill Books, 1997)
* Snaps: Poetry and Prose from a Family Album (Rose Hill Books, 1994)<ref>{{cite web|last=Elkins|first=James R.|title=Strangers to Us All|url=http://lawlit.net/lp-2001/pommersheim.html|publisher=Lawyers and Poetry|accessdate=June 21, 2019}}</ref>

